pe":"contributions","id":"39838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107239"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for interpretation of a screening test result. You review a recent study evaluating a new screening test for breast cancer. The study included 1,000 women. Of the 50 women who actually had cancer, the test correctly identified 40 of them. Of the 950 women without cancer, the test incorrectly indicated cancer in 180 of them.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the sensitivity of this screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["82%","80%","18%","95%","97%"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of diagnostic test characteristics using a two-by-two table. Among people who actually have the condition, some will test positive (correctly identified cases) and some will test negative (missed cases).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;width:60%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECancer Present\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECancer Absent\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETest Positive\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E40 (True Positive)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E180 (False Positive)\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETest Negative\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E10 (False Negative)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E770 (True Negative)\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E80%\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct sensitivity. Sensitivity is calculated by dividing the number of correctly identified cases (40) by the total number of people who actually have cancer (50). Therefore, 40/50 = 80%. This means the test correctly identifies 80% of people who actually have cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E18%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the positive predictive value, which is the probability that someone with a positive test actually has cancer. It is calculated by dividing the number of correctly identified cases (40) by the total number of positive test results (220).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E95%\u003C/strong\u003E is close to but not equal to the negative predictive value, which is the probability that someone with a negative test is truly disease-free. It is calculated by dividing the number of people correctly identified as not having cancer (770) by the total number of negative test results (780).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E82%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the specificity, which is the proportion of people without cancer who test negative. It is calculated by dividing the number of people correctly identified as not having cancer (770) by the total number of people without cancer (950).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E97%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the accuracy, which is the overall proportion of correct test results. It is calculated by dividing the total number of correct results (810) by the total number of people tested (1000).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey formulae for diagnostic test characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESensitivity = True Positives / (True Positives + False Negatives)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESpecificity = True Negatives / (True Negatives + False Positives)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPositive Predictive Value = True Positives / (True Positives + False Positives)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENegative Predictive Value = True Negatives / (True Negatives + False Negatives)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAccuracy = (True Positives + True Negatives) / Total Population\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these test characteristics is crucial for interpreting diagnostic tests in clinical practice. Sensitivity is particularly important for screening tests where missing cases would be particularly concerning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sensitivity is calculated as the number of correctly identified cases divided by total number of people with the condition.","Sensitivity represents the proportion of people with a condition who test positive.","Two-by-two tables are useful tools for calculating diagnostic test characteristics."],"references":["Trevethan R. Sensitivity, Specificity, and Predictive Values: Foundations, Pliabilities, and Pitfalls in Research and Practice. Front Public Health. 2017;5:307. Published 2017 Nov 20. doi:10.3389/fpubh.2017.00307"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T20:14:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T20:21:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8185"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107239"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"